{
  "What is the SI unit of electric charge?": "",
  "Volt (V)": "",
  "Ohm (Ω)": "",
  "Ampere (A)": "",
  "Coulomb (C)": "",
  "The SI unit of electric charge is the coulomb (C). One coulomb equals the charge of approximately 6.24 × 10¹⁸ elementary charges (protons or electrons).": "",
  "The elementary charge (charge on a single proton) is approximately:": "",
  "1.6 × 10⁻¹⁹ C": "",
  "6.02 × 10²³ C": "",
  "1.6 × 10⁻¹² C": "",
  "9.0 × 10⁹ C": "",
  "The elementary charge e = 1.6 × 10⁻¹⁹ C. Protons carry +e and electrons carry −e. All observable charges are integer multiples of this fundamental unit.": "",
  "Two point charges of +2 μC and −2 μC are separated by 0.1 m. What is the magnitude of the electrostatic force between them? (k = 9 × 10⁹ N·m²/C²)": "",
  "36 N": "",
  "3.6 N": "",
  "0.36 N": "",
  "0.036 N": "",
  "F = kq₁q₂/r² = (9 × 10⁹)(2 × 10⁻⁶)(2 × 10⁻⁶)/(0.1)² = (9 × 10⁹)(4 × 10⁻¹²)/0.01 = 0.036/0.01 = 3.6 N.": "",
  "If the distance between two charged objects is tripled, the electrostatic force between them:": "",
  "Becomes one-ninth as strong": "",
  "Triples": "",
  "Becomes one-third as strong": "",
  "Becomes nine times as strong": "",
  "Coulomb's law: F ∝ 1/r². Tripling r gives F_new = F/(3²) = F/9. The force follows an inverse-square law.": "",
  "A positively charged rod is brought near an uncharged metal sphere without touching it. The side of the sphere nearest the rod becomes:": "",
  "Both positively and negatively charged simultaneously": "",
  "Positively charged": "",
  "Negatively charged": "",
  "Unchanged": "",
  "By electrostatic induction, the positive rod attracts free electrons in the metal to the near side, making it negative, while the far side becomes positive. The sphere's net charge remains zero.": "",
  "Electric charge is conserved, meaning:": "",
  "Charge can be destroyed but not created": "",
  "Only positive charges are conserved": "",
  "The total electric charge in an isolated system remains constant": "",
  "Charge can be created if enough energy is available": "",
  "Conservation of charge is a fundamental law: electric charge cannot be created or destroyed. Charge can be transferred between objects, but the total charge of an isolated system remains constant.": "",
  "Two identical conducting spheres carry charges of +6 μC and −2 μC. They are brought into contact and then separated. What charge does each carry afterward?": "",
  "0 μC each": "",
  "+3 μC each": "",
  "+2 μC each": "",
  "+4 μC each": "",
  "Total charge = +6 + (−2) = +4 μC. When identical conductors touch, charge distributes equally: each gets +4/2 = +2 μC.": "",
  "Materials in which electrons can move freely are called:": "",
  "Superconductors only": "",
  "Insulators": "",
  "Semiconductors": "",
  "Conductors": "",
  "Conductors (like metals) have free electrons that move easily through the material, allowing charge to flow. Insulators restrict electron movement.": "",
  "Like charges (both positive or both negative) will:": "",
  "Repel each other": "",
  "Have no interaction": "",
  "Cancel each other out": "",
  "Attract each other": "",
  "Like charges repel and opposite charges attract. This is a fundamental property of electric charge described by Coulomb's law.": "",
  "The Coulomb constant k in Coulomb's law has a value of approximately:": "",
  "9.0 × 10⁹ N·m²/C²": "",
  "6.67 × 10⁻¹¹ N·m²/kg²": "",
  "8.85 × 10⁻¹² C²/(N·m²)": "",
  "1.6 × 10⁻¹⁹ N·m²/C²": "",
  "Coulomb's constant k = 9.0 × 10⁹ N·m²/C². The value 6.67 × 10⁻¹¹ is the gravitational constant G, and 8.85 × 10⁻¹² is the permittivity of free space ε₀.": "",
  "What is 'Coulomb's law'?": "",
  "The law stating that the electrostatic force between two point charges is proportional to the product of their charges and inversely proportional to the square of their separation": "",
  "The law relating current, voltage, and resistance, since the prevailing theory about Coulomb would support this particular interpretation": "",
  "The law relating electric field to charge density due to the well-established relationship between Coulomb trends and broader outcomes": "",
  "The law governing magnetic forces on wires given that prevailing Coulomb conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "Coulomb's law: F = kq₁q₂/r² describes the electrostatic force between two point charges. It is analogous in form to Newton's law of gravitation but much stronger.": "",
  "What does 'electric field' mean?": "",
  "The force between two magnets in most scenarios involving field factors": "",
  "The flow of electrons through a wire according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "A region of space around a charged object where another charge would experience an electric force": "",
  "The energy stored in a capacitor according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "An electric field E exists around any charged object. It represents the force per unit positive test charge: E = F/q. Field lines point away from positive charges and toward negative charges.": "",
  "What is 'electrostatic induction'?": "",
  "The flow of charge through a conductor": "",
  "The creation of current by a changing magnetic field": "",
  "The redistribution of charges on an object caused by a nearby charged object without direct contact": "",
  "Charging an object by rubbing it with another material": "",
  "Electrostatic induction is the process by which a charged object causes a redistribution of charges on a nearby conductor without touching it, creating regions of positive and negative charge.": "",
  "What is an 'insulator'?": "",
  "A material that only conducts at high temperatures": "",
  "A material that stores magnetic energy": "",
  "A material that conducts electricity well": "",
  "A material that strongly resists the flow of electric charge": "",
  "An insulator (like glass, rubber, or plastic) is a material in which electrons are tightly bound to atoms and do not move freely, strongly resisting the flow of electric charge.": "",
  "What does 'grounding' mean in electricity?": "",
  "Placing a charged object on the ground physically": "",
  "Removing all charge from an object by heating it": "",
  "Surrounding an object with an insulating material": "",
  "Connecting a charged object to the Earth to allow excess charge to flow to or from the ground, neutralizing the object": "",
  "Grounding connects a charged object to Earth via a conductor. The Earth acts as a virtually infinite charge reservoir, absorbing or supplying electrons to neutralize the object.": "",
  "What does 'quantization of charge' mean?": "",
  "Electric charge exists only in integer multiples of the elementary charge e": "",
  "Charge is always positive": "",
  "Charge can take any continuous value": "",
  "Charge depends on the mass of the object": "",
  "Charge quantization means all observed charges are integer multiples of e = 1.6 × 10⁻¹⁹ C. You cannot have a charge of 0.5e; charge comes in discrete packets.": "",
  "What is a 'semiconductor'?": "",
  "A material with electrical conductivity between that of a conductor and an insulator, whose conductivity can be controlled": "",
  "A material that is half conductor and half magnet": "",
  "A material that conducts electricity only when dissolved in water": "",
  "A perfect insulator at all temperatures": "",
  "Semiconductors (like silicon and germanium) have conductivity between conductors and insulators. Their conductivity can be modified by temperature, light, or adding impurities (doping), making them essential for electronics.": "",
  "What does 'charging by contact' mean?": "",
  "Charging an object by placing it near another charged object": "",
  "Transferring charge from one object to another by physically touching them together": "",
  "Generating charge using a battery": "",
  "Creating charge through a chemical reaction": "",
  "Charging by contact (conduction) involves physically touching a charged object to an uncharged one. Charge flows from one to the other until they reach the same potential, giving both the same sign of charge.": "",
  "What is 'electric flux'?": "",
  "A measure of the number of electric field lines passing through a surface": "",
  "The rate of flow of electric current": "",
  "The voltage across a capacitor": "",
  "The energy stored in an electric field": "",
  "Electric flux (Φ_E) is the total electric field passing through a surface: Φ_E = E·A·cos(θ). Gauss's law relates the net flux through a closed surface to the enclosed charge.": "",
  "What does 'superposition principle' mean for electric forces?": "",
  "Electric forces only act between two charges at a time": "",
  "Electric forces from multiple charges cancel out completely": "",
  "The net force on a charge is the vector sum of the individual forces from each other charge": "",
  "Only the closest charge contributes to the force": "",
  "The superposition principle states that the net electric force on a charge equals the vector sum of the individual Coulomb forces from every other charge. Each pair interaction is independent.": "",
  "A Van de Graaff generator in a science museum accumulates charge on its metal dome. A child touches the dome and their hair stands on end. Which principle explains the hair standing up?": "",
  "Like charges on individual hair strands repel each other": "",
  "Gravitational effects of the charge": "",
  "Static electricity removes the hair's mass": "",
  "Magnetic repulsion between hair strands": "",
  "When the child touches the dome, charge transfers to their body and hair. Each hair strand acquires the same sign of charge. Like charges repel, causing the strands to push apart and stand on end.": "",
  "A photocopier works by first charging a drum uniformly, then projecting an image onto it that removes charge in lit areas. Toner particles (charged opposite to the drum) stick to the remaining charged areas. This process primarily uses:": "",
  "Magnetic attraction": "",
  "Chemical bonding": "",
  "Electrostatic attraction between opposite charges": "",
  "Gravitational settling": "",
  "Photocopiers (xerography) rely on electrostatic attraction. Toner with charge opposite to the drum's remaining charge is attracted to and sticks to charged areas, reproducing the image.": "",
  "During a thunderstorm, the bottom of a cloud has a large negative charge. This induces a positive charge on the ground below. When the electric field becomes strong enough, lightning strikes. If the cloud base is 1000 m above the ground and the breakdown field of air is about 3 × 10⁶ V/m, what approximate voltage between cloud and ground triggers lightning?": "",
  "About 3 × 10¹² V (3 trillion volts)": "",
  "About 3 × 10³ V (3 thousand volts)": "",
  "About 3 × 10⁹ V (3 billion volts)": "",
  "About 3 × 10⁶ V (3 million volts)": "",
  "V = E × d = 3 × 10⁶ V/m × 1000 m = 3 × 10⁹ V. In practice, stepped leaders reduce the effective gap, so actual breakdown occurs at somewhat lower voltages.": "",
  "An electrostatic precipitator in a coal power plant removes soot particles from exhaust. Particles pass through a region where they acquire negative charge, then are attracted to positively charged collection plates. If a soot particle with charge −3 × 10⁻¹⁵ C is in an electric field of 5000 N/C, what force acts on it?": "",
  "1.5 × 10⁻⁸ N": "",
  "1.5 × 10⁻¹¹ N": "",
  "1.5 × 10⁻¹⁵ N": "",
  "1.5 × 10⁻³ N": "",
  "F = qE = 3 × 10⁻¹⁵ × 5000 = 1.5 × 10⁻¹¹ N. Though tiny, this force is sufficient to deflect small soot particles onto the collection plates.": "",
  "A laser printer charges a photoconductor drum to −600 V. A laser then discharges specific spots, and positively charged toner sticks to those discharged areas. If the drum has a capacitance of 10 nF, how much charge was initially on the drum?": "",
  "6 × 10⁻⁶ C": "",
  "6 × 10⁻⁹ C": "",
  "60 C": "",
  "6 × 10⁻³ C": "",
  "Q = CV = 10 × 10⁻⁹ F × 600 V = 6 × 10⁻⁶ C = 6 μC.": "",
  "A student shuffles across a carpet and accumulates −0.5 μC of charge. She then touches a metal doorknob, producing a spark. If the spark transfers all the charge in 1 millisecond, what is the average current during the spark?": "",
  "0.5 A": "",
  "0.5 mA": "",
  "5 A": "",
  "0.5 μA": "",
  "I = Q/t = 0.5 × 10⁻⁶ C / 1 × 10⁻³ s = 5 × 10⁻⁴ A = 0.5 mA. Though the current is small, the high voltage makes the spark noticeable.": "",
  "Three charges are arranged in a line: +4 μC at x = 0, −2 μC at x = 3 m, and +1 μC at x = 5 m. What is the direction of the net force on the −2 μC charge?": "",
  "The net force is zero": "",
  "Toward the right (+x direction)": "",
  "Toward the left (−x direction)": "",
  "Perpendicular to the line": "",
  "The +4 μC charge at x=0 attracts the −2 μC charge to the left. The +1 μC charge at x=5 attracts the −2 μC charge to the right. Since +4 μC is larger and closer (3 m vs 2 m), the net force is toward the left.": "",
  "Electrostatic spray painting applies a negative charge to paint droplets, which are then attracted to a grounded (positively induced) car body. This technique reduces paint waste because:": "",
  "The paint dries faster when charged": "",
  "Static electricity makes the paint thicker": "",
  "The paint is heated to stick better": "",
  "Charged droplets are attracted to the surface from all directions and wrap around edges": "",
  "Charged paint droplets are attracted to the grounded surface electrostatically. The electric field lines curve around the object, causing droplets to coat even hidden surfaces and edges, reducing overspray waste significantly.": "",
  "A Faraday ice pail experiment places a charged ball inside a hollow conductor without touching it. An electroscope attached to the outside shows a deflection. When the ball is removed, the electroscope returns to zero. This demonstrates:": "",
  "Magnetic fields are generated inside the conductor": "",
  "Charge can be created inside a conductor": "",
  "Electrostatic induction: the charged ball induces opposite charge on the inner surface and same-sign charge on the outer surface": "",
  "Charge is destroyed when placed inside a conductor": "",
  "The charged ball induces opposite charge on the conductor's inner surface and same-sign charge on its outer surface. The outer charge causes the electroscope deflection. Removing the ball allows charges to recombine.": "",
  "An inkjet printer uses electric fields to steer tiny charged ink droplets onto paper. If a droplet with charge 1.5 × 10⁻¹³ C passes between two plates separated by 2 mm with a voltage of 1000 V between them, what electric force acts on the droplet?": "",
  "7.5 × 10⁻⁸ N": "",
  "1.5 × 10⁻¹⁰ N": "",
  "7.5 × 10⁻⁵ N": "",
  "7.5 × 10⁻¹¹ N": "",
  "E = V/d = 1000/0.002 = 500,000 V/m. F = qE = 1.5 × 10⁻¹³ × 500,000 = 7.5 × 10⁻⁸ N. This force steers the droplet to the correct position on the page.": ""
